gomodel:SYNGO_324  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: An ADCY1 knockout is used to demonstrate that cAMP production by adenylyl cyclase 1 (AC1) is required mossy fiber LTP.\n\n- Knockout of AC1 leads to a strong reduction in cAMP production in hippocampal neurons (figure 1-2).\n- Mossy fiber LTP is strongly reduced in the knockout (figure 6).\n- Forskolin (an agonist of PKA, the major downstream effector of cAMP) is still able to potentiate synaptic transmission in the knockout (figure 8). This shows that pathways downstream of cAMP production are intact.\n\nNumerous studies have demonstrated that mossy fiber LTP is expressed presynaptically (Zalutsky & Nicoll), and requires cAMP production and the activation of PKA. Since this form of LTP does not induce changes in presynaptic calcium influx (Kamiya et.al 2002), it must operate through potentiation of synaptic vesicle exocytosis.. Experimental description: AC1 null mice (Wu et al., 1995) were back-crossed 12 generations into 129JR2448 mice to obtain mutant mice in a uniform genetic background." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7620-2704" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1558-1958" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-19" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_324" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

